'''''Bedsitcom''''' is a British [[reality television]] series that was broadcast on [[Channel 4]] in December 2003. Pitched as "somewhere between a sitcom and a reality TV show",<ref name="How real is reality TV?"/> the show documented the lives of six young people living in a [[Apartment|loft flat]] in London. Its [[Narrative hook|hook]] was that its TV audience was aware that three of the participants<U+2014>named Mel, Paul and Rufus<U+2014>were actually actors being directed by a trio of "writers" in a garage on the ground floor.

''Bedsitcom'' was commissioned by the [[Channel Four Television Corporation]] and produced by [[Objective Productions]]. Producers auditioned thousands of people to be the show's genuine contestants and selected from them six young adults to live in the flat with the three actors. These six contestants were told that they would be starring in a new reality TV series called ''Making Friends'', and featured on the show three at a time over a period of eight weeks. The programme ran for a single series of eight episodes and featured various storylines, involving dead goldfish, dodgy dealings, promiscuous mothers and telephone psychics.

The show received largely negative feedback from television reviewers, who criticised the show's premise as a "deeply offensive" idea.<ref name="New low hit by reality sickcom"/> It received a viewership peak of 1.2&nbsp;million with its final episode, giving it an audience share of 8.9&nbsp;per cent. ''Bedsitcom'' was not recommissioned for a second series and is currently not available either on DVD on Channel&nbsp;4's [[Video on demand|on demand]] service, [[4oD]].

==Production==
===Concept===
''Bedsitcom'' was conceived as a parody of both reality television and the traditional [[sitcom]],<ref name="How real is reality TV?"/> and was created by [[Peter James (writer)|Peter James]] and [[Andrew O'Connor (actor)|Andrew O'Connor]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=A professional approach to murder|first=David|last=Charters|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-special-features/2008/08/29/a-professional-approach-to-murder-64375-21630290/|newspaper=[[Liverpool Daily Post]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[Liverpool]]|date=29 August 2008|oclc=500344194|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref name="Independent">{{Cite news|title=Andrew O'Connor: My Life In Media|first=Oliver|last=Duff|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/andrew-oconnor-my-life-in-media-496655.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print|location=[[London]]|issn=0951-9467|oclc=185201487|date=27 July 2005|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> ''Bedsitcom'' combined these two elements by featuring three members of the public being unknowingly placed in extraordinary situations by three actors being directed by writers.<ref name="The Times">{{Cite news|title=The future looks bright for the boy who gave birth to his twin, but the same cannot be said for the new reality show Bedsitcom|first=Joe|last=Joseph|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1037591.ece|newspaper=[[The Times]]|publisher=[[News Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|issn=0140-0460|oclc=6967919|date=9 December 2003|accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref>{{Sfn|Mason|2003|p=1}} After being commissioned for [[Channel 4]] by Danielle Lux, ''Bedsitcom'' was produced by Matt Crook and Kirsty Smith of [[Objective Productions]].<ref name="Bedsit comedy falls flat"/><ref name="BFI"/>

The show was pitched as "somewhere between a sitcom and a reality TV show"<ref name="How real is reality TV?">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/interviews/a12572/how-real-is-reality-tv.html|title=How real is reality TV?|first=Neil|last=Wilkes|date=2 December 2003|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref> and was promoted as "an entirely new genre of television programme".<ref name="Bedsit comedy falls flat">{{Cite news|title=Bedsit comedy falls flat|first=Victor|last=Lewis-Smith|authorlink=Victor_Lewis-Smith|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|location=[[London]]|oclc=123896151|date=9 December 2003}}</ref> Its title is a [[portmanteau]] of the words "[[bedsit]]"<U+2014>a British term referring to a form of rented accommodation consisting of a single room and shared bathroom<U+2014>and "sitcom". The title is technically a [[misnomer]]: as the accommodation's bedroom and sitting area were separate, it was not a bedsit.<ref name="Double jeopardy">{{Cite news|title=Double jeopardy|first=Rupert|last=Smith|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2003/dec/09/broadcasting.tvandradio|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|location=[[London]]|issn=0261-3077|oclc=60623878|date=9 December 2003|accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref>

===Casting===
[[Image:Bedsitcomcast1.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A man in glasses, a blue sweater and jeans, a man in a white shirt, a man in a black sweater, a woman in a black top and blue jeans, a man in a green T-shirt and blue jeans and a woman in a white top and a blue denim skirt sit in a large, well-lit room filled with modern furniture. The man in the black sweater is sitting on the floor; the rest are on chairs or stools.|The first generation of cast in ''Bedsitcom''. From left to right: Paul, [[Rufus Jones (actor)|Rufus]], Bob, Shirine, Dave and Mel.]]
[[Image:Bedsitcomcast2.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A man in glasses, a white shirt and blue jeans, a woman in a white top and white trousers, a man in a brown leather jacket and a white T-shirt, a man in a cap, red hoodie and white trousers, a man in a white patterned shirt and a woman in a black top and denim skirt sit on three yellow bean bag chair in a large, well-lit room with modern furniture.|The second generation of cast in ''Bedsitcom''. From left to right: Paul, Mel, David, Barrington, [[Rufus Jones (actor)|Rufus]] and Jessica.]]
Melanie Ash, Paul Gibbon and [[Rufus Jones (actor)|Rufus Jones]] were selected as the three actors to feature in ''Bedsitcom''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/bedsitcom/show/23556/cast.html|title=Bedsitcom Cast and Crew|publisher=[[TV.com]]|accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref> Jones had previously portrayed the part of Crispin in the 2002 drama ''[[White Teeth#Television adaptation|White Teeth]]'';<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/teeth/whos_who_credits.html|title=''White Teeth'' Cast and Credits|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service]]|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref> Gibbon had played the lead role of Link in the series ''[[Stone Cold (novel)#Television|Stone Cold]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0173255/|title=Stone Cold|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref> To avoid breaking character, all three used their real names while living in the flat and went through weeks of rehearsals. O'Connor described the entire process as "exhausting".<ref name="How real is reality TV?"/>

To find suitable candidates to live with the three actors, producers auditioned roughly 10,000 people, who were told that they would be taking part in a new reality television programme in London called ''Making Friends''.<ref name="My flatmates are acting a bit weird.">{{Cite news|title=My flatmates are acting a bit weird.|first=Sarah|last=Knapton|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/My+flatmates+are+acting+a+bit+weird.-a0111642046|newspaper=[[Evening Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]|date=26 December 2003|accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref> Six members of the public, named Barrington, Bob, Dave, David, Jessica and Shirine, were selected to feature on the show.

===Writing and filming===
The plots for ''Bedsitcom'' were devised by a team of writers located in a garage on the ground floor of the apartment building that the contestants were staying in. The writers would often appear on screen and explain to the TV audience what their intention for each episode was.{{Sfn|Piper|2004|p=283}} They communicated with Ash, Gibbon and Jones either by ringing them on their mobile phones, or by calling them downstairs to speak to them in person.<ref name="Mark Lawson"/> The writers would occasionally change their plans for an episode<U+2014>in "Worst Case Scenario", for example, the writers altered their storyline from having Mel bring various animals into the flat to having the group kill Mel's goldfish after only one night.<ref name="How real is reality TV?"/>

Among the team of writers were [[Jesse Armstrong]] and [[Sam Bain]], who had created the Channel 4 sitcom ''[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]'' with O'Connor earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/the-peep-show-team-are-magicians|title=The Peep Show team are Magicians|date=11 August 2006|publisher=[[Total Film]]|accessdate=7 April 2011|quote=...&nbsp;The team who make Channel 4<U+2019>s Peep Show <U+2013> actors Robert Webb and David Mitchell, alongside director Andrew O<U+2019>Connor and writers Sam Bain and Jesse Armstrong.&nbsp;...}}</ref> Filming of ''Bedsitcom'' began in May 2003 and lasted for approximately eight weeks.<ref name="My flatmates are acting a bit weird."/> The flatmates were filmed for 12 hours a day, with this footage then being edited down to roughly 25 minutes per week of filming.<ref name="How real is reality TV?"/>

==Episodes==
''Bedsitcom'' documented the lives of six young adults living in a loft flat in London.<ref name="Scotsman">{{Cite news|title=Live feed. The day TV turned on its audience|first=Tom|last=Lappin|url=http://living.scotsman.com/features/Live-feed-The-day-TV.2485286.jp|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]|location=[[Edinburgh]]|date=8 December 2003|issn=0307-5850|oclc=614655655|accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref> Eight episodes in total were created, which were divided into two distinct halves.<ref name="BFI">{{Cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/39891|title=Bedsitcom|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref> The first four episodes centred on the lives of Mel, Paul and Rufus, the three actors, as they lived in the flat with Bob, Dave and Shirine, the three unaware members of the public who believed they were taking part in a genuine reality TV show. After Bob, Dave and Shirine had learnt the true nature of the show at the end of episode four they moved out and were replaced by three new members of the public named Barrington, David and Jessica. These three new cast members remained on ''Bedsitcom'' for the final four episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/bedsitcom/show/23556/episode.html|title=Bedsitcom Season 1 Episode Guide|publisher=[[TV.com]]|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.locatetv.com/tv/bedsitcom/142745/episode-guide|title=Bedsitcom <U+2013> Episode Guide|publisher=LocateTV|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref>
