==Reception==
===Critical reception===
Reviewers gave ''Bedsitcom'' generally negative feedback. Some were critical of the storylines that had been devised by the writers, calling them unimaginative and clich<U+00E9>d.<ref name="Bedsit comedy falls flat"/><ref name="INNIT"/> Others were critical of the premise of the show itself, describing it as "deeply offensive and manipulative"<ref name="New low hit by reality sickcom">{{Cite news|title=LAST NIGHT'S TV: New low hit by reality sickcom.|first=Alun|last=Palmer|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/LAST+NIGHT%27S+TV%3A+New+low+hit+by+reality+sickcom.-a0111044589|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[London]]|date=9 December 2003|oclc=223228477|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref> and "morally reprehensible"<ref name="INNIT">{{Cite news|title=IT'S A LAUGH, INNIT?|first=Jaci|last=Stephen|newspaper=[[The Mail on Sunday]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|location=[[London]]|date=9 December 2003|oclc=300483910}}</ref><U+2014>all three actors, particularly Jones, received criticism for their acting abilities.<ref name="New low hit by reality sickcom"/><ref name="Bedsit comedy falls flat"/><ref name="Scotsman"/> Frances Traynor of ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|The Daily Record]]'' called the show "about as funny as sharing a flat with that German cannibal"<ref>{{Cite news|title=FRANCES TRAYNOR: DID YOU SEE...?|first=Frances|last=Traynor|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FRANCES+TRAYNOR%3a+DID+YOU+SEE...%3f-a0111129652|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|The Daily Record]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[Glasgow]]|date=11 December 2003|issn=0956-8069|oclc=500344244|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref> and Paddy Sherman of ''[[Liverpool Echo|The Liverpool Echo]]'' branded the show "intensely irritating".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Paddy Shennan: A real honour?|first=Paddy|last=Sherman|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Paddy+Shennan%3a+A+real+honour%3f-a0111250206|newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[Liverpool]]|date=9 December 2003|issn=1751-6277|oclc=500165464|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref> Paul Hoggart of ''[[The Times]]'' called it "a show that seemed to have nothing to recommend it whatsoever",<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bedsitcom|first=Paul|last=Hoggart|newspaper=[[The Times]]|publisher=[[News Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|date=12 December 2003|issn=0140-0460|oclc=6967919}}</ref><U+2014>after watching the first episode, Charlie Catchpole of ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]]'' simply stated: "It isn't funny."<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bedsitcom|first=Charlie|last=Catchpole|newspaper=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]]|publisher=[[Northern & Shell]]|location=[[London]]|date=9 December 2003|oclc=53210766}}</ref> Critics on ''[[Newsnight Review]]'' also spoke harshly about the programme, with [[Tom Paulin]] calling it "a disgraceful piece of television" and [[Jeanette Winterson]] describing it as "incredibly dull".<ref name="Newsnight">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/review/3301155.stm|title=Bedsitcom|date=8 December 2003|publisher=[[BBC News]]|location=[[London]]|accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref>

{{Quote box
|width=30em
|bgcolor=lightblue
|quote="Bedsitcom might have worked as a 90-minute one-off with the unveiling at the end. By spinning out the encounter over almost eight hours, this punningly titled series suggests that a more honest title would have been: Flat."
|source=<U+2014> [[Mark Lawson]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref name="Mark Lawson"/>
}}
A slightly more positive review came from Joe Joseph of ''[[The Times]]'', who suggested that "if it [the format] works, [it] could be profitably franchised around the world".<ref name="The Times"/> [[Deborah Bull]] said that, while it was "a terrible programme", there were "some funny lines".<ref name="Newsnight"/> Chris Wilson, editor of [[Collective (BBC)|Collective]], similarly wrote that "while the end results are often amusing and tackle some interesting storylines, the whole project smacks of lazy, cruel television".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/collective/A2082548|title=Reality TV gets desperate.|first=Chris|last=Wilson|date=28 November 2003|publisher=[[Collective (BBC)|Collective]]|accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref>

In a 2005 interview, series creator Andrew O'Connor spoke about ''Bedsitcom'' and the critical reaction that it had received. He said that he felt that the premise of the show was a "great idea", but that it did not make "great television".<ref name="Independent"/> He also remarked: "We didn't cast it right and the public didn't take to the series."<ref name="Independent"/>

===Television ratings===
Given the level of exposure and promotion that it had been granted, [[Channel Four Television Corporation|Channel Four]] were disappointed by ratings for ''Bedsitcom''. The pilot, shown on 8 December 2003, generated 1&nbsp;million viewers, but this figure had fallen to 700,000 by 10 December. The ratings rose to 1.1&nbsp;million viewers for the fourth episode, "Fag Ends".<ref name="Broadcast"/> On average, the series attracted an audience share of less than 6&nbsp;per cent.{{Sfn|Piper|2004|p=283}} The final episode, "P.I.G", gained a viewership of 1.2&nbsp;million with a market share of 8.9&nbsp;per cent, which was its highest audience for the series.<ref name="Broadcast">{{Cite journal|date=19 December 2003|title=Bedsitcom ends with just 1.2m|journal=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|location=[[London]]|publisher=[[International Thomson]]|editor1-first=Lisa|editor1-last=Campbell|oclc=60625607}}</ref>

===Awards===
''Bedsitcom'' was nominated for a single award at the 2004 [[Rose d'Or]] festival, a European awards show that commemorates achievement in entertainment television. The programme was submitted in the Best Situation Comedy category, but was beaten by ''[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]''.<ref name="Award"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Peep Show: A sneaky peep at the show|first=Andy|last=Welch|url=http://www.flintshirechronicle.co.uk/entertainment-flintshire/2009/09/21/peep-show-a-sneaky-peep-at-the-show-59067-24743947/|newspaper=[[Flintshire Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[Llandudno]]|issn=1751-3146|oclc=500164467|date=21 September 2009|accessdate=5 April 2011|quote=...&nbsp;the show has managed to scoop a prestigious Rose d'Or award for Best European Sitcom&nbsp;...}}</ref>
{|class="wikitable"
